summary:
The Security Council:
Recalling its resolutions on Western Sahara, reaffirms resolution 1429 (2002), and stresses the need for a political solution to the dispute. 
The Council is concerned about the suffering of the people of Western Sahara, potential instability in the region, and the obstruction of economic development. 
It reaffirms its commitment to assist the parties in achieving a just, lasting, and mutually acceptable solution, providing for self-determination of the people of Western Sahara. 
The Council commends the parties for their commitment to the ceasefire and welcomes the contribution of MINURSO. 
It supports the efforts of the Secretary-General and his Personal Envoy, and the Peace plan for self-determination of the people of Western Sahara. 
The Council:
1. Supports the Peace plan as an optimum solution;
2. Calls upon parties to work with the UN and each other towards its implementation;
3. Calls for cooperation with the Secretary-General and his Personal Envoy;
4. Urges the Polisario Front to release prisoners of war and cooperate with the International Committee of the Red Cross;
5. Calls for collaboration with UNHCR in confidence-building measures and urges the international community to support UNHCR and the World Food Programme;
6. Extends the mandate of MINURSO until 31 October 2003;
7. Requests a report on progress made before the end of the present mandate;
8. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
